, Cheshire, England","of Tattenhale, Chester, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England","Leegomery, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Touchet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Anastasie, Denys, Evest, Minos, Rodolph, Vernice.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a small grove, from a diminutive of Old French <i>toche</i> ‘grove’.","History: René Touchet from Thorigné-d'Anjou in Maine-et-Loire, France, married Marie Caillé in Saint-Laurent, Île-de-Montreal, QC, in 1746."],"variants":[{"name":"Touchette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Pierre, Armand, Collette, Euclide, Henri, Hilaire, Huguette.","Altered form of French   Touchet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":64,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":99,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Touchet was born about 1160, in Buglawton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Simon Touchet of Tackley and Willington, was 26 and his mother, Alice de Coleville, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Alice de Cumbre."},"et":{"about 1160–":"umbes 1160–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1164–Female":"1164–Surnud","1192–1234":"1192–1234","1136–1203":"1136–1203","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1203":"1203","LVG ABT 1300":"umbes 1300","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1234":"1234","1164":"1164","about 1157":"umbes 1157","1160":"1160","1192":"1192","Tattenhall, Cheshire, England":"Tattenhall, Cheshire, England","of Tattenhale, Chester, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglaw